<!-- CONTENT SECTIONS -->
<div class="content-wrap">

  <section class="content-section" aria-labelledby="what-h2">
    <h2 id="what-h2">What Is the Healthcare Workers CRS Calculator? (2026 Guide)</h2>
    <div class="answer-box">
      <strong>Quick Answer:</strong> The Healthcare Workers CRS Calculator estimates your Express Entry CRS score for Canada's healthcare category-based draws. Healthcare workers in NOC TEER 1–3 occupations (nurses, doctors, pharmacists, etc.) can receive ITAs at CRS cutoffs as low as 430 — far below the all-program cutoff of 493+.
    </div>
    <p>Canada actively targets healthcare workers through <strong>category-based Express Entry draws</strong> introduced in June 2023. These draws pull exclusively from candidates whose primary NOC occupation is on the <a href="https://www.canada.ca/en/immigration-refugees-citizenship/services/immigrate-canada/express-entry/submit-profile/rounds-invitations/category-based-selection.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRCC healthcare target list</a>, meaning qualified healthcare workers can receive an Invitation to Apply (ITA) at a much lower CRS score than general pool applicants.</p>
    <p>This free calculator applies the official <a href="https://www.canada.ca/en/immigration-refugees-citizenship/services/immigrate-canada/express-entry/eligibility/criteria-comprehensive-ranking-system/grid.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRCC CRS points grid</a> to your profile and compares your score against recent healthcare draw cutoffs. All healthcare NOC codes are covered — from specialist physicians (31100) to licensed practical nurses (32301) to dental hygienists (32101). No login or personal information is required.</p>

    <h3>Why Healthcare Workers Have a Major Advantage in 2026</h3>
    <table class="data-table" aria-label="Healthcare vs all-program draw comparison">
      <thead><tr><th>Draw Type</th><th>Typical 2024–2026 Cutoff</th><th>Healthcare Eligible?</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Healthcare Category</strong></td><td><span class="score-chip blue">430–471</span></td><td>✅ Yes — exclusive</td></tr>
        <tr><td>All-Program Draw</td><td><span class="score-chip">493–520</span></td><td>✅ Yes — open to all</td></tr>
        <tr><td>STEM Category</td><td><span class="score-chip">486–510</span></td><td>⚠️ Only if NOC qualifies</td></tr>
        <tr><td>French Language Draw</td><td><span class="score-chip">393–430</span></td><td>✅ With NCLC 7+</td></tr>
        <tr><td>PNP Draw</td><td><span class="score-chip">786–802</span></td><td>✅ With nomination</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p style="font-size:0.78rem;color:var(--text-muted);">Source: <a href="https://www.canada.ca/en/immigration-refugees-citizenship/services/immigrate-canada/express-entry/rounds-invitations.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRCC Express Entry Rounds of Invitations</a>. See full history at our <a href="/cutoff-scores">CRS Cutoff Scores</a> page.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section" aria-labelledby="noc-h2">
    <h2 id="noc-h2">Healthcare NOC Codes Eligible for Express Entry Category Draws</h2>
    <div class="answer-box">
      <strong>Quick Answer:</strong> IRCC targets specific NOC TEER 1–3 healthcare occupations for category-based draws. This covers doctors, nurses, pharmacists, dentists, physiotherapists, medical lab technologists, and many more. Confirm your exact NOC via the <a href="https://noc.esdc.gc.ca/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ESDC NOC tool</a>.
    </div>
    <table class="data-table" aria-label="Healthcare NOC codes for Express Entry">
      <thead><tr><th>NOC Code</th><th>Occupation</th><th>TEER</th><th>Min. Language</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>31100</td><td>Specialist physicians</td><td>1</td><td>CLB 7</td></tr>
        <tr><td>31102</td><td>General practitioners &amp; family physicians</td><td>1</td><td>CLB 7</td></tr>
        <tr><td>31103</td><td>Dentists</td><td>1</td><td>CLB 7</td></tr>
        <tr><td>31110</td><td>Pharmacists</td><td>1</td><td>CLB 7</td></tr>
        <tr><td>31120</td><td>Dietitians &amp; nutritionists</td><td>1</td><td>CLB 7</td></tr>
        <tr><td>31200</td><td>Audiologists &amp; speech-language pathologists</td><td>1</td><td>CLB 7</td></tr>
        <tr><td>31201</td><td>Physiotherapists</td><td>1</td><td>CLB 7</td></tr>
        <tr><td>31202</td><td>Occupational therapists</td><td>1</td><td>CLB 7</td></tr>
        <tr><td>31301</td><td>Registered nurses &amp; registered psychiatric nurses</td><td>1</td><td>CLB 7</td></tr>
        <tr><td>31302</td><td>Nurse practitioners</td><td>1</td><td>CLB 7</td></tr>
        <tr><td>32101</td><td>Dental hygienists</td><td>2</td><td>CLB 5</td></tr>
        <tr><td>32103</td><td>Medical laboratory technologists</td><td>2</td><td>CLB 5</td></tr>
        <tr><td>32104</td><td>Respiratory therapists</td><td>2</td><td>CLB 5</td></tr>
        <tr><td>32110</td><td>Medical sonographers</td><td>2</td><td>CLB 5</td></tr>
        <tr><td>32301</td><td>Licensed practical nurses</td><td>2</td><td>CLB 5</td></tr>
        <tr><td>33102</td><td>Nurse aides, orderlies, patient service associates</td><td>3</td><td>CLB 4</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p style="font-size:0.78rem;color:var(--text-muted);">This is a non-exhaustive list. Always confirm with the <a href="https://www.canada.ca/en/immigration-refugees-citizenship/services/immigrate-canada/express-entry/submit-profile/rounds-invitations/category-based-selection.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">official IRCC category-based selection page</a>. NOC TEER 1 roles qualify via FSW or CEC; TEER 2–3 via CEC or FST.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section" aria-labelledby="how-use-h2">
    <h2 id="how-use-h2">How to Use This Healthcare CRS Calculator</h2>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="step-text"><strong>Select Your Healthcare NOC Code</strong> — Pick your occupation from the dropdown. The calculator will show whether you're eligible for the healthcare category draw and flag which Express Entry stream (FSW, CEC, FST) applies.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="step-text"><strong>Enter Core Human Capital Factors</strong> — Age and education have the largest impact. A physician with a professional degree (MD, DDS) earns 135 CRS points for education vs. 30 for a secondary diploma.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="step-text"><strong>Add Language CLB Scores</strong> — CLB 9 earns ~116 CRS points in language vs. CLB 7's ~60 points. Even CLB 8 makes a huge difference. Use our <a href="/clb-scores">IELTS to CLB Converter</a> to confirm your level.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="step-text"><strong>Add Work Experience</strong> — Canadian healthcare experience is worth significantly more than foreign experience. Even 1 year working in a Canadian hospital or clinic on a work permit adds 40 CRS points.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="step-text"><strong>Add Bonus Points &amp; Choose Draw Target</strong> — A PNP nomination adds +600 pts. Select "Healthcare Category" as your draw target to see if your score exceeds the ~430–471 cutoff range for dedicated healthcare draws.</div></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section" aria-labelledby="boost-h2">
    <h2 id="boost-h2">How to Improve Your Healthcare Workers CRS Score</h2>
    <div class="answer-box">
      <strong>Quick Answer:</strong> For healthcare workers, improving language scores above CLB 7 is the fastest way to boost CRS. Moving from CLB 7 to CLB 9 can add 50+ CRS points and push you well above the healthcare draw cutoff.
    </div>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Score CLB 9+ on language (IELTS 7.5+)</strong> — Language is your biggest lever. CLB 9 earns 29 pts per skill vs 15 for CLB 7 — that's 56 extra CRS points across all 4 skills. Use our <a href="/clb-scores">CLB converter</a> to plan your target band scores.</li>
      <li><strong>Get Canadian work experience in healthcare</strong> — Working 1 year on a healthcare work permit (e.g., under an LMIA or bridging permit) adds 40 CRS pts and also helps provincial licensing progress.</li>
      <li><strong>Apply for provincial healthcare pathways</strong> — Many provinces have dedicated healthcare streams. Ontario's OINP has a healthcare workers stream. Alberta's AAIP has pathways for nurses and physicians. Use our <a href="/ontario-crs-calculator">Ontario</a> and <a href="/alberta-crs-calculator">Alberta</a> calculators.</li>
      <li><strong>Get a valid Canadian job offer</strong> — A healthcare job offer from a Canadian employer (LMIA-based or LMIA-exempt) adds +50 CRS pts and significantly helps with provincial licensing applications.</li>
      <li><strong>Learn French</strong> — NCLC 7+ in French with English CLB 5+ adds +50 CRS pts and opens French Language category draws (cutoff ~393), far lower than all-program.</li>
      <li><strong>Target multiple draw types</strong> — As a healthcare worker, you're eligible for Healthcare Category, All-Program, French Language (with French skills), and PNP draws. Submit your profile and wait for whichever draw comes first.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>For all 10 strategies with detailed explanations, see our <a href="/improve-score">Improve Your CRS Score guide</a>.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section" aria-labelledby="pathway-h2">
    <h2 id="pathway-h2">Which Express Entry Stream Should Healthcare Workers Use?</h2>
    <div class="answer-box">
      <strong>Quick Answer:</strong> Use FSW if you have foreign healthcare experience (no Canadian experience required). Use CEC if you already have 1+ year of Canadian healthcare work. Both make you eligible for healthcare category draws.
    </div>
    <table class="data-table" aria-label="Express Entry streams for healthcare workers">
      <thead><tr><th>Stream</th><th>Best For Healthcare Workers When...</th><th>Min. Language</th><th>Key Requirement</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong><a href="/fsw-crs-calculator">FSW</a></strong></td><td>You have foreign healthcare experience (NOC TEER 0/1)</td><td>CLB 7</td><td>1yr foreign work exp + 67-point grid</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong><a href="/cec-calculator">CEC</a></strong></td><td>You have 1yr+ Canadian healthcare work exp (TEER 1/2/3)</td><td>CLB 7 (T0/1), CLB 5 (T2/3)</td><td>1yr Canadian work in last 3 years</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong><a href="/fst-crs-calculator">FST</a></strong></td><td>Dental hygienist, medical lab tech, other TEER 2/3 trades</td><td>CLB 5 (R/W), CLB 4 (S/L)</td><td>2yr trade work + job offer or certification</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong><a href="/pnp-calculator">PNP</a></strong></td><td>You qualify for a province's healthcare stream</td><td>Varies by province</td><td>Provincial nomination (+600 CRS)</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>If you qualify for both FSW and CEC, calculate scores for both using our <a href="/fsw-crs-calculator">FSW Calculator</a> and <a href="/cec-calculator">CEC Calculator</a> — your CEC score is usually higher if you have Canadian experience.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section" aria-labelledby="faq-h2">
    <h2 id="faq-h2">Frequently Asked Questions — Healthcare Workers CRS Calculator</h2>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faq1">What CRS score do healthcare workers need for Canada in 2026?<span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></button>
      <div class="faq-a" id="faq1">Healthcare workers need approximately 430–471 CRS for dedicated healthcare category draws in 2026. This is significantly lower than the all-program cutoff of 493–520. The lowest healthcare category draw cutoff was 430 in January 2024. Aim for 470+ to be competitive across multiple healthcare draws. Even if you miss a healthcare draw, you remain eligible for all-program draws.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faq2">Does Canada have a dedicated immigration program for nurses?<span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></button>
      <div class="faq-a" id="faq2">Yes. Registered nurses (NOC 31301) and nurse practitioners (NOC 31302) qualify for Canada's healthcare category-based Express Entry draws. Many provinces also have dedicated nursing pathways: Ontario's OINP Healthcare Workers stream, Nova Scotia's Skilled Worker stream, and British Columbia's PNP Health Authority stream. Use our <a href="/pnp-calculator">PNP Calculator</a> to check provincial options. You must still meet the base Express Entry eligibility (language, work experience) to enter the pool.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faq3">Can internationally educated doctors (IMGs) apply through Express Entry?<span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></button>
      <div class="faq-a" id="faq3">Yes. Specialist physicians (NOC 31100) and general practitioners (NOC 31102) both qualify for Express Entry through FSW (if they have 1yr+ of foreign clinical work in their NOC). A Canadian medical license is not required to receive an ITA or become a PR — but you will need provincial licensing (CPSO, CPSBC, etc.) to practice medicine in Canada. Many provinces have assessment and bridging programs for IMGs. Check the <a href="https://physiciansapply.ca/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Physicians Apply</a> portal for details.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faq4">How often does IRCC hold healthcare category draws?<span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></button>
      <div class="faq-a" id="faq4">IRCC held its first healthcare category draw in June 2023. Since then, healthcare draws have occurred approximately 3–5 times per year, typically every 6–8 weeks. There is no fixed schedule — IRCC announces draws with 24–48 hours' notice. The best strategy is to submit your Express Entry profile as soon as you're eligible and maintain or improve your CRS score while waiting. See our <a href="/cutoff-scores">CRS Cutoff Scores history</a> for all past draws.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faq5">Is IELTS mandatory for healthcare workers applying to Canada?<span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></button>
      <div class="faq-a" id="faq5">A language test is mandatory for Express Entry. You can use IELTS General Training or CELPIP-General for English, or TEF Canada/TCF Canada for French. IELTS Academic (taken for medical licensing) is not accepted for immigration. FSW healthcare roles require CLB 7 minimum in all 4 skills (IELTS 6.0/6.0/6.0/6.0). Higher scores earn more CRS points. Use our <a href="/clb-scores">IELTS to CLB Converter</a> to check your exact CLB level.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faq6">Can pharmacists and dental hygienists get a healthcare category draw ITA?<span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></button>
      <div class="faq-a" id="faq6">Yes. Both pharmacists (NOC 31110, TEER 1) and dental hygienists (NOC 32101, TEER 2) are on IRCC's healthcare category target list. Pharmacists must qualify through FSW (1yr foreign experience, CLB 7) or CEC (1yr Canadian experience). Dental hygienists can qualify through FST or CEC with CLB 5 minimum. In healthcare draws, both occupations are included, meaning they can receive ITAs at the lower healthcare cutoff (430–471) rather than the all-program cutoff (493–520).</div>
    </div>

  </section>

  <section class="content-section" aria-labelledby="tools-h2">
